Good with a comment to explain the difference between of and 0. I do however this we do the check just one bit better. In general (as you noticed) it can give some problems to check whether something is None, simply by checking if it evaluates to False, if there is another valid input that also evaluates to False (like 0). However, a slightly cleaner way to do is to simply check whether variable is None, that way the checks can be rewritten to:

```python
if sleep_time_seconds is None:
    sleep_time = ''
elif sleep_time_seconds != int(sleep_time_seconds):
    ....
else:
    ....
```

